#compdef kue-dashboard
# =============================================================================
# kue-dashboard — TJ Holowaychuk + Automattic's "kue"
#          Web UI launcher — the canonical browser-
#          based dashboard for kue, the Node.js
#          priority job queue backed by Redis.
#          Provides at-a-glance views of active /
#          inactive / completed / failed / delayed
#          jobs, per-job detail pages with payload +
#          progress + error stack traces, manual
#          retry + remove actions, and search by job
#          type + state.
#          Distinguishing from BullMQ's `bull-board`
#          (felixmosh/bull-board; the modern
#          replacement for the Bull/BullMQ family of
#          queues), Sidekiq Web (Ruby; for the
#          Sidekiq Ruby queue), Flower (Python; for
#          Celery), asynqmon (R770 Go=100 LANDMARK;
#          for hibiken/asynq), AdminBro / forest-
#          admin (general-purpose admin panels not
#          queue-specific), and the deprecated kue-
#          gui Electron desktop app by:
#            - NODE-REDIS FOUNDATION — uses
#              redis/node-redis ~2.6 (this is the
#              headline CLI library that CLOSES Axis
#              45 on the TS-Node side at 1/1/1 AND
#              marks the **100-LIBRARY-PER-LANGUAGE
#              LANDMARK** on the TS-Node side; see
#              taxonomy notes below) for ALL kue
#              queue interaction.  node-redis is the
#              official Redis-team-maintained
#              Node.js client; ~18,500+ stars on the
#              underlying library
#            - YARGS-BASED CLI — single command with
#              three short flags (`-r`, `-p`, `-q`)
#              + standard `-h` / `--help`.  Built
#              on yargs ^4 (TJ Holowaychuk's family
#              of related Node CLI libraries — same
#              author as commander, express, mocha)
#            - PROCESS-EMBEDDED EXPRESS SERVER —
#              `kue.app.listen(port)` mounts the
#              Express-based admin app on the chosen
#              port; no separate server install
#              needed; ideal for development +
#              small-team deployments
#            - PUG VIEW RENDERING — uses pug (formerly
#              jade) v2 templating for the admin HTML;
#              templates ship as part of the kue npm
#              package; users get a single `npm
#              install -g kue` + `kue-dashboard`
#              command sequence to get a working
#              dashboard
#            - STYLUS + NIB STYLING — uses stylus +
#              nib for the dashboard CSS; the same
#              styling stack TJ Holowaychuk popularized
#              for Express-based Node web apps in the
#              early-2010s
#            - REDIS URL VIA -r — `-r redis://10.0.
#              0.4:6379` connects to any Redis
#              instance reachable via standard Redis
#              URL syntax (supports password +
#              database selection inline via
#              redis://user:pass@host:port/dbnum)
#            - DASHBOARD PORT VIA -p — `-p 3050`
#              changes the bound port from the
#              default 3000.  Useful when port 3000
#              is in use by other Node services
#              (which is most of the time in dev
#              environments)
#            - QUEUE PREFIX VIA -q — `-q myapp`
#              changes the Redis key prefix from the
#              default `q` to a custom value.
#              Critical when multiple applications
#              share a single Redis instance + need
#              namespaced queue storage to avoid
#              cross-app interference
#            - BODY-PARSER + EXPRESS 4 — uses body-
#              parser + Express 4.x for the form
#              handling on retry/remove actions;
#              users can POST to /job/{id}/retry +
#              /job/{id}/remove from custom tooling
#              + curl
#            - NODE-REDIS-WARLOCK DISTRIBUTED LOCK
#              — uses node-redis-warlock ~0.2 for
#              the queue's distributed locking
#              semantics; ensures only one worker
#              processes any given job at a time
#              across a horizontally-scaled worker
#              pool
#            - LODASH UTILITIES — uses lodash ^4 for
#              the dashboard's collection-traversal
#              utilities (rendering nested job
#              payloads, formatting timestamps, etc.)
#            - 9,443+ STARS ON Automattic/kue —
#              one of the longest-running Node.js
#              Redis-backed queue libraries (founded
#              2011); Automattic-sponsored
#              (WordPress.com parent company);
#              maintenance has slowed in recent
#              years as the Node community migrated
#              to Bull/BullMQ but kue + kue-
#              dashboard remain widely deployed in
#              legacy production stacks
#          Used by: legacy Node.js applications
#          that adopted kue in the 2011-2017 era
#          (before Bull's rise) + haven't migrated
#          yet, operations teams maintaining kue-
#          backed services who need a web dashboard
#          for queue introspection, and developers
#          learning Node.js queue patterns from
#          historical examples since kue is one of
#          the simplest queue implementations to
#          read end-to-end.
#
# Author:  TJ Holowaychuk (original author; also
#          author of Express, Commander, Mocha,
#          Pug, Stylus — many of the foundational
#          Node.js libraries from the 2011-2014
#          era) + Automattic engineering team
#          (sponsors of WordPress.com + Tumblr +
#          WooCommerce); ongoing maintenance under
#          Automattic/kue.
# Source:  https://github.com/Automattic/kue
#          https://github.com/Automattic/kue/blob/master/bin/kue-dashboard
#          https://github.com/Automattic/kue/blob/master/package.json
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `kue-dashboard
#          --help` shows yargs-generated help.
#          Full kue API + dashboard docs at
#          https://github.com/Automattic/kue/blob/
#          master/Readme.md (extensive examples).
# Library: redis ~2.6 (the legacy "node-redis" npm
#          package, predecessor to the modern
#          redis/node-redis v4 line; both maintained
#          by Redis Inc).  This is the headline
#          dependency for this completion's axis-45
#          closing role AND the marker library for
#          the 100-LIBRARY-PER-LANGUAGE TS-Node
#          landmark; see taxonomy notes below.  Also
#          express ^4.12 (Axis 26 web framework),
#          body-parser ^1.12, yargs ^4 (Axis 1
#          argparse), lodash ^4 (utilities), pug
#          ^2.0.0-beta3 (templating), stylus ~0.54
#          + nib ~1.1 (CSS), node-redis-warlock
#          ~0.2 (distributed lock helper for kue).
# License: MIT
# Status:  9,443+ stars on Automattic/kue; in
#          MAINTENANCE mode (not actively developed
#          in recent years; the Node community has
#          largely migrated to Bull/BullMQ +
#          felixmosh/bull-board).  kue + kue-
#          dashboard remain widely deployed in
#          legacy production stacks where migration
#          cost outweighs incremental benefit
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY — AXIS 45 CLOSES AT 1/1/1 +
#   **100-LIBRARY-PER-LANGUAGE LANDMARK (TS-Node side)** +
#   **THREE-LANGUAGE 100-LIBRARY TRIFECTA COMPLETE**
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This completion **CLOSES AXIS 45 AT 1/1/1 THREE-
# LANGUAGE SYMMETRY** AND marks the **100-LIBRARY-
# PER-LANGUAGE LANDMARK on the TS-Node side** — the
# third and final of three consecutive 100-library
# milestones crossing in three sequential leader-
# bump rounds:
#   * R769 Rust=100 LANDMARK (flowgger/redis-rs)
#   * R770 Go=100 LANDMARK (asynqmon/go-redis)
#   * R771 TS-Node=100 LANDMARK (kue-dashboard/node-
#     redis) ← THIS
#
# Pattern: R768 124th language (HVML/PurC) closes
# the prior 3+1 cycle → R769 Rust=100 LANDMARK
# (flowgger/redis-rs OPENS Axis 45) → R770 Go=100
# LANDMARK (asynqmon/go-redis continues Axis 45) →
# R771 TS-Node=100 LANDMARK (kue-dashboard/node-
# redis CLOSES Axis 45 AT 1/1/1 THIS ROUND).
# Next R772 will be the 125th language closing
# the 3+1 micro-cycle.
#
# THE COMPLETE AXIS 45 PICTURE (NOW 1/1/1) +
# THREE-LANGUAGE 100-LIBRARY TRIFECTA:
#
#   * RUST = redis-rs (R769 flowgger — Rust 100
#     LANDMARK)
#     - mitsuhiko/redis-rs (Armin Ronacher's
#       canonical Rust Redis client); ~3,800 stars
#     - Pattern: REDIS-AS-INPUT-PIPELINE (flowgger
#       subscribes to Redis lists for data
#       collection)
#
#   * GO = go-redis (R770 asynqmon — Go 100
#     LANDMARK)
#     - redis/go-redis (Vladimir Mihailenco + Redis
#       team's official Go Redis client); ~22,120
#       stars
#     - Pattern: REDIS-AS-QUEUE-BACKEND (asynqmon
#       visualizes asynq's Redis-stored task queue
#       state via web UI)
#
#   * TS-NODE = node-redis (R771 THIS — TS-Node 100
#     LANDMARK)
#     - redis/node-redis (Redis Inc's official
#       Node.js client; ~18,500 stars on the
#       underlying library)
#     - Pattern: REDIS-AS-QUEUE-BACKEND (kue-
#       dashboard visualizes kue's Redis-stored job
#       queue state via web UI; functional twin of
#       asynqmon in the Node.js ecosystem)
#
# THE AXIS 45 ARC TELLS THE COMPLETE REDIS-CLIENT-
# AS-CLI STORY + THE THREE-LANGUAGE 100-LIBRARY
# TRIFECTA STORY:
#
#   - R769 flowgger (Rust REDIS-INPUT) — Frank
#     Denis pedigree + AWS Labs corporate sponsor
#     + ISC license + Logstash-alternative
#     positioning
#   - R770 asynqmon (Go REDIS-QUEUE-UI) — Ken
#     Hibino (Google) + asynq ecosystem + MIT
#     license + Web UI deployment pattern
#   - R771 kue-dashboard (TS-Node REDIS-QUEUE-UI)
#     — TJ Holowaychuk + Automattic + MIT license
#     + the elder Node.js queue ecosystem that
#     pre-dates the modern Bull/BullMQ family
#
# Each language's representative LIBRARY is the
# dominant Redis client in its ecosystem.  Each
# language's representative CLI demonstrates a
# DIFFERENT Redis-centric workflow:
#   * Stream-collection (flowgger)
#   * Queue introspection (asynqmon + kue-
#     dashboard, functional twins across Go + TS-
#     Node)
#
# Cross-language CLI library taxonomy after R771:
#   * 124 languages
#   * 480 total CLI library variants (**Rust 100** /
#     **Go 100** / **TS-Node 100**)
#   * **TRIPLE 100-LIBRARY LANDMARK COMPLETED** —
#     ALL THREE LEADER LANGUAGES at exactly 100
#     CLI libraries each; the first time the corpus
