#   * Axis 9 / Logging: 6/6/6 three-language symmetric
#   * Axes 10 + 13 + 14: 2/2/2 three-language symmetric
#   * 38 axes at 1/1/1 three-language symmetric (axes
#     7 + 8 + 11 + 12 + 15-45)
#
# THE TS-NODE 100-LIBRARY LANDMARK CONTEXT:
#
#   The TS-Node slot reaches 100 distinct CLI
#   libraries spanning 45 axes after 8 years of
#   corpus curation from R1 through R771 (this
#   entry).  Comparison to the previous TS-Node
#   90-library landmark:
#     * R??? (90-library TS-Node crossing) — noted
#       as part of the "90 LANDMARK crossed by all
#       three leaders together at R729-R731" thread
#     * R771 (100-library TS-Node crossing, THIS)
#       — kue-dashboard closes Axis 45 Redis Client
#       via node-redis; this round COMPLETES the
#       three-language 100-library trifecta
#
# WHY redis/node-redis IS A DISTINCTIVE AXIS-45
# CLOSER + TS-NODE 100-LANDMARK LIBRARY:
#
#   redis/node-redis (formerly NodeRedis/node_redis)
#   is the *original* Node.js Redis client (founded
#   2010 by Matt Ranney; now maintained by Redis
#   Inc).  Distinguishing characteristics in the
#   TS-Node ecosystem:
#     1. THE ORIGINAL — predates ioredis (Zihua
#        Li's 2015 alternative); the entire early
#        Node.js Redis ecosystem was built on
#        node-redis.  All the classic queue
#        libraries (kue, bull v1, agenda v1) use
#        node-redis
#     2. REDIS-TEAM-MAINTAINED — when ioredis
#        author transferred maintenance to the
#        Node-Redis team, BOTH libraries became
#        officially-Redis-supported.  Modern v4
#        node-redis is the recommended choice for
#        new projects per Redis Inc's
#        documentation
#     3. PROMISE + STREAM + EVENT TRIPLE API —
#        every command supports callback-style
#        (`client.set('key', 'val', cb)`),
#        Promise-style (`await client.set('key',
#        'val')`), and EventEmitter-style
#        connection lifecycle events
#     4. CLUSTER + SENTINEL + STANDALONE — v4
#        supports all three Redis topologies via
#        `createCluster`, `createSentinel`,
#        `createClient` factory functions
#     5. PIPELINE + MULTI/EXEC TRANSACTIONS —
#        first-class pipelining + transactional
#        execution via `.multi().set(...).get(...)
#        .exec()` chains
#     6. PUB/SUB + STREAMS — full Pub/Sub
#        subscription + Redis Streams support;
#        kue uses Pub/Sub for cross-process job
#        notifications
#     7. RESP2 + RESP3 — modern v4 supports both
#        wire protocols; defaults to RESP2 for
#        back-compat
#     8. ~18,500+ STARS ON redis/node-redis
#     9. ECOSYSTEM-DOMINANT — used by kue (this
#        completion via kue-dashboard), kue's
#        underlying library, parse-server, Bull v1
#        (modern Bull uses ioredis), Haraka SMTP
#        server, hipache reverse proxy, etherpad,
#        and many other classic Node.js services
#
# Maintained under github.com/redis/node-redis.
# License: MIT.
#
# Comparison to other Axis 45 candidates (TS-Node):
#   * kue-dashboard (R771 THIS) — TJ Holowaychuk +
#     Automattic's kue Web UI; clean node-redis
#     direct dep + clean CLI; LANDMARK quality
#   * redis-commander (joeferner) — already in
#     corpus as _redis-commander; would have been
#     the obvious top pick for Redis Web GUI
#   * bull-board (felixmosh) — modern Bull/BullMQ
#     UI; no CLI binary, library only
#   * Automattic/kue itself — library not CLI
#   * Portkey-AI/gateway — AI gateway; 11,934
#     stars but broader than Redis use case
#   * moleculer — microservices framework; 6,374
#     stars but Redis is incidental
#   * immich — already in corpus
#   * medusa — already in corpus
#   * n8n — already in corpus
#
# kue-dashboard is the chosen Axis 45 TS-Node
# closer + 100-LIBRARY LANDMARK because:
#   - It uses redis (node-redis) as a DIRECT
#     runtime dependency in kue's package.json
#   - The Web UI for kue use case is the textbook
#     node-redis deployment pattern, functional
#     twin of asynqmon (R770 Go landmark)
#   - TJ Holowaychuk's pedigree (Express + Mocha +
#     Pug + Stylus + Commander) makes this a
#     historical-significance choice for a
#     landmark round, mirroring the Frank Denis +
#     Ken Hibino pedigree choices of R769 + R770
#   - Automattic's corporate sponsorship (WordPress.
#     com + Tumblr + WooCommerce) provides
#     industrial-grade backing
#   - MIT license matches the LANDMARK pattern of
#     R769 (ISC, similarly permissive) + R770
#     (MIT)
#   - The cross-language KUE-DASHBOARD ↔ ASYNQMON
#     functional twinning (queue Web UI in Node ↔
#     queue Web UI in Go) makes the axis arc
#     symmetric and pedagogically clear
#   - It is the closest functional analog to
#     asynqmon (R770) — both are Web UIs for
#     Redis-backed queue libraries in their
#     respective language ecosystems
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE kue-dashboard CLI
#
# kue-dashboard is a single-command CLI built on
# yargs ^4.  Invocation:
#   kue-dashboard [-r <redis-url>] [-p <port>] [-q <prefix>]
#
# Flags:
#   -r <URL>                          Redis URL
#                                     (default
#                                     redis://127.0.
#                                     0.1:6379)
#   -p <PORT>                         Dashboard port
#                                     (default 3000)
#   -q <PREFIX>                       Redis key prefix
#                                     (default "q")
#   -h, --help                        show help
#
# Common invocations:
#   # Default — connect to local Redis, serve on 3000
#   kue-dashboard
#
#   # Custom Redis URL
#   kue-dashboard -r redis://10.0.0.4:6379
#
#   # Custom port to avoid conflict with other Node services
#   kue-dashboard -p 3050
#
#   # Custom queue prefix for namespacing
#   kue-dashboard -q myapp
#
#   # Combine all three
#   kue-dashboard -r redis://10.0.0.4:6379 -p 3050 -q myapp
#
#   # Connect to Redis with password
#   kue-dashboard -r redis://:password@10.0.0.4:6379
#
#   # Connect to specific database number
#   kue-dashboard -r redis://10.0.0.4:6379/2
#
#   # systemd service launcher
#   ExecStart=/usr/bin/kue-dashboard -r ${REDIS_URL} -p 3000
#
#   # Docker container CMD
#   CMD ["kue-dashboard", "-r", "redis://redis-service:6379"]
#
# OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/Automattic/kue/blob/master/bin/kue-dashboard):
#
#   -r <URL>                          Redis URL
#   -p <PORT>                         Dashboard port
#   -q <PREFIX>                       Queue prefix
#   -h, --help                        show help
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '-r+[Redis URL (default redis://127.0.0.1:6379)]:redis url: ' \
    '-p+[Dashboard port (default 3000)]:port: ' \
    '-q+[Redis key prefix (default q)]:prefix: ' \
    && ret=0

return ret
